<author><name><![CDATA[CartCollector]]></name></author>
<updated>2007-03-25T14:06:34-07:00</updated>
<published>2007-03-25T14:06:34-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3105&amp;p=22623#p22623</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3105&amp;p=22623#p22623"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[What is VROM?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3105&amp;p=22623#p22623"><![CDATA[
Yes. VROM (or CHR-ROM) is a ROM chip inside a NES cartridge that contains all of the "tile data" (the bitmaps of the 8 pixel by 8 pixel "tiles" used to make up the background and sprites). However, what colors the background/sprites are (the palette) and where they go (name tables, SPR-RAM) have to be loaded into the PPU's VRAM by the CPU.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1345">CartCollector</a> — Sun Mar 25, 2007 2:06 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
